{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600593/1930092801/0318.xml":{"full_text":"News of Markets\nPages 1 to 4\nPart 6\u201414 Pages\nDISTRICT BANKERS\nLEAVE TOR ANNUAL\nGATHERING IN WEST\nIddlson Heads Delegation to\nConvention\u2014Vital Ques\ntions to Be Discussed.\nRDDRESS BY PRESIDENT\nWILL FEATURE PROGRAM\nHoover It Expected to Present Im\nportant Data on Business\nConditions.\nT BY EDWARD C. STONE.\nMembers of Washington's delegation\nId the annual convention of the Amer\nican Bankers\u2019 Association, at Cleve\nland, are on their way to attend the\naessions of the most important gather\ning of the Nation's financiers in 1930.\nThis year's session is considered the\nBlast vital held in several years, on ac\ncount of the business situation all over\nthe country, the agricultural situation\nand the constantly growing controversy\nover unit, branch, chain and group\nbanking, which is sure to be one of\nthe big problems before Congress dur\ning the next 12 months. Sweeping\nchanges In banking trends and meth\nods will be discussed.\nThe highlight among the addresses\ntrill be President Hoover\u2019s speech.\nBankers expect the President will delve\nInto the very latest developments in\nthe national business outlook and prob\nably present valuable Government in\nformation Intended to show that busi\nness has really turned the comer.\nPresident John G. Lonsdale will pre\naide at the general sessions. The na\ntional bank, trust company, savings\nbank, clearing house and many other\n\u25a0actions will also hold important group\nmeetings, at which their particular\nproblems will be considered.\nThe delegation from this city is\nBeaded by Francis a. Addison, Jr.,\npresident of the Security Savings St\nCommercial Bank, who represents the\nDistrict Bankers\u2019 Association on the\nA. B. A. executive council. Robert V.\nnaming, president of the Riggs Na\ntional Bank, who has served on several\nnational committees during the past\npear, will also attend the convention.\nController of the Currency John W.\nPole and Deputy Controller F. G.\nAwait are to represent the United\nStates Treasury. E. E. Mountjoy,\nWashington representative of the Na\ntional Bank Division of the A. B. A.,\n\u201c\u201cWill also be present, having left Wash\nington yesterday.\nAmong other local bankers Cleve\nland-bound are Joshua Evans, Jr.,\npresident of the District National\nBank; Maurice Otter back, president of\nthe Anacostia Bank; Sidney F. Talia\nferro of the Riggs National and Ber\ntram Cheaterman, president of the\nMorris Flan Bank. Miss Mary J. Win\nfree, one of the leading woman bank\ners in the Capital, will represent the\nCommercial National and M. H. Cal\nnan, cashier of the Liberty National,\nwill be another local financier In at\ntendance.\nIt Is anticipated that more than\n1,000 bankers will register. When the\nconvention was held in Washington\nseveral years kgo, more than 3,500 at\ntended the meetings here. Since that\ntene the annual attendance has grown\nsteadily. The next A. B. A. president,\nRome C. Stephenson, has a wide per\nsonal acquaintance in the Capital, and\nIt Is safe to aay he will not forget local\nfinanciers when he names his impor\ntant committees for next year.\nLsaa Associations\u2019 Big Assets.\nFifty-five building and loan associa\ntions belonging to the United States\nBuilding and Loan League now have\nbesets exceeding $10,000,000 each, ac\ncording to H. F. Cellarius, secretary\ntreasurer, of Cincinnati.\nAfter reporting the 55 associations\nbrlth more than $10,000,000, the report\ntoes on and gives a list of 19 associa\ntions with assets exceeding $20,000,000\neach. The Perpetual Building Associa\ntion of this city stands twelfth in this\nlist, the local association reporting as\nsets amounting to $23,026,159.\nPacific States Savings St Loan Co. of\nBan Francisco has the largest assets of\nbny association in the country, showing\ncm June 30 last $65,367,061. In second\nplaoe Is the Railroad Co-operative\nBuilding Sc Loan Association of New\nYork City, with $59,656,455, followed\nBy the Farm St Home Savings Sc Loan\nAssociation, Nevada, Mo., with $53,-\n000,000.\nJust ahead of the Washington asso\nciation in the list is the Conservative\nSavings St Loan Association, Omaha,\nNebr., with assets of $28,331,217, while\nJust below the Perpetual is the Local\nBuilding St Loan Association, Oklahoma\nCity, Okla.\n304 Institute Enrollments.\nAt the close of the first week of the\nVail term enrollments in Washington\nChapter, American Institute of Bank\ning, have reached 306, according to an\nnouncement by Aubrey O. Dooley,\nchairman of the Educational Commit\ntee. During the past week classes were\nInaugurated In banking fundamentals,\ncommercial law, negotiable Instruments,\neconomics, credits. Investments, public\ndiscussion and debate and a special\nclass for bank women dealing with\nproblems in personal efficiency. With\nstill another week before enrollments\nclose for the Fall term, chapter officials\nexpressed confidence that approxi\nmately 350 students will have enrolled\nby next Friday.\nSuch a record would manifestly show\nthe Intense interest of local bankers in\nInstitute training, because this not only\nmarks the first year Washington Chap\nter has conducted all of its classes oh\ntuition fee basis, but it has also in\ncreased class attendance requirements\nfrom 65 per cent to 75 per cent and!\nunder the new institute program re\nquires the completion of seven sub\njects, which necessitates 294 hours of\nclass work, with an average passing\ngrade of 75 per cent In each subject,\nbefore a student Is awarded the stand\nard certificate of the American Insti\ntute of Banking.\nIt is announced that the enrollments\nIn the special class for women, under\nthe direction of Anne Tillery Renshaw,\nhas exceeded the limit of 22 students,\nand a second class in that course, with\n22 additional students already enrolled,\nwill be conducted on Wednesday eve\nning from S to 9:30 p.m. The class in\nEubilc discussion and debate, of which\nv. George Farnham is instructor, has\nalso practically reached its capacity.\nt QUARTERLY DIVIDEND.\nWILMINGTON, Del., September 27\n'{Special).\u2014The regular quarterly divi\ndend of $1.75 on the company\u2019s prefer\nred stock was declared by the directors\nof the Hercules Powder Co. today. The\ndividend is payable November 15 to\nI ateakholders of record November 4.\n\u2022Trade Trend and Outlook\nWalter C. Teagle, Standard Oil Executive Finds\nVolume of Business and Employment at\nPresent Time Is Fairly Satisfactory.\nNote\u2014Ttie Star and North American 1\nNewspaper Alliance have planned a series\nof articles dealing with present condi\ntions in the business world and contain\ning forecasts of the immediate future.\nThe first of these articles follows:\nBY WALTER C. TEAGLE,\nPresident Standard Oil Company of New\nJersey, ss told to J. V. Fitzgerald.\nThere has been so much talk about\nthe decline in business that I\u00abm rather\npleasantly surprised by the discovery\nthat the situation is not as disturbing\nas it has been made\nout to be. Reports\nby some of the\nlargest employers of\nlabor, dealing with\nthe state of their\nbusiness, their\nearnings and their\npersonnel policy\nhave Just come to\nhand.\nAs might be ex\npected, these re\nports waft not the\nmost cheerful kind\nlof reading. The\nI general burden was\nI a story of reduced\nsales, smaller net\nearnings and some\nwh a t widespread\nWalter C. Teasle.\ncontraction in the number of workers.\nThese reports express the view, how\never, that we have reached the low level\nof business and that any change which\ncomes in the next few months should\nbe on the side of improvement.\nSuch conditions as exist are always\npart of the aftermath of a period of\nextraordinary activity. It is human\nI nature always to shoot at new high rec\nords. Every industry wants to show a\ni substantial gam each month over cor\nresponding periods of previous years,\ni and when these gains fail to material\nise there immediately springs up talk\nof depression.\nPrevious Period Abnormal.\nNow if we remember that the first\n10 months of 1929 was a period of un\nusual prosperity, and compare condi\ntions today with what we might con\nsider a normal amount of business, the\nfact Is that the volume of trade and\nemployment today is fairly satisfactory.\nIn many lines it is better than a nor\nmal average taken over any recent\nperiod of years. The fact that we are\nnot up to the totals reported a year\nago is not to my mind evidence of any\nserious disruption of our business\nprogress.\nThe petroleum industry has fared\nrelatively better than most other lines.\nIn fact, for the first six months of 1930\nthere was an increase of more than 9\nper cent in the consumption of gasoline,\nas compared with the first half of 1929,\nwhen prosperity was running high.\nWhile profits in the oil business have\ndeclined this year because of the low\nlevel of prices prevailing, there has\nbeen practically no reduction in the\nnumber of men employed or in wages\npaid. The volume of business lately has\nbeen about the same as a year ago,\nwithout the customary gains, but the\noversupply of petroleum products has\nbrought about such extreme competi\ntion as to make retail prices much too\nlow.\nIt is generally true today that the\npublic is buying motor fuel at the coat I\nof raw material plus transportation, re\nfining and marketing expense. At\nprices now quoted even the most skill\nful and economical management found\nit difficult to make a profit. In fact,\nthe average refiner will do well if he\ngets back 100 cents for every dollar he\nis paying out for material and services.\nOil Business Bound.\nConsequently, if we look at the oil\nbusiness from the standpoint ot the\nstock market speculator concerned al\nmost exclusively with immediate re\nturns, we find it disappointing. No\n(me would invest his capital in an en\nterprise that little more than breaks\neven when it does the largest volume\nof business in its history.\nNevertheless and notwithstanding\nthis present unsatisfactory situation,\nthe economics of the petroleum indus\ntry today are sounder than a year ago,\nwhen it was earning substantial profits.\nThis simply means that what was fore\nseen a year ago has now come to pass,\nand with corrective measures at work\nwe are that much nearer the return\nto a sound basts.\nThe oil business has the same diffi\nculties as other lines when it seeks to\nmarket Its products. It offers a field\nwide open for competitive capital and\ncompetitive sales effort. As is true in\nso many other fields now, the petro\nleum industry has Increased facilities\nof'production more rapidly than war\nranted for the demand for the manu\nfactured product. It has therefore\nbeen engaged for some time in accu\nmulating a surplus after satisfying all\ncurrent demands. This surplus, though\neuphoniously referred to as a reserve,\nis, in fact, a worrisome liability.\nWhile each yearly accumulation has\namounted to but a small percentage of\nthe year\u2019s consumption, the total has\nnow reached proportions where it ex\nerts a great deal of pressure on the\nmachinery of price making. Instead\nof being a servant to the industry, as\nh true oil reserve should, this surplus\nhas turned master and dictated terms\nto the Industry responsible for its cre\nation.\nMultiplicity ot Stations.\nThis competition has brought about\nfacilities for distributing petroleum\nproducts far in excess of true require\nments. Each service station built on\na good traffic corner has seemed to act\nas a challenge to a competing com\npany to match it with another station\nacross the street. It is evident to any\none that where there are 10 service\nstations in a town that supplies busi\nness enough to keep only 3 reasonably\nbusy, the total expense of 7 stations is\nuneconomic, and with the division of\nbusiness the result is Insufficient earn\nings for all ten.\nAnother angle of this* unfortunate\ncompetition is that when a company\ninstalls a new station In a field where\nit cannot Increase total consumption\nby as much as a gallon, it must take\nits business from the trade already\nhandled by the companies earlier in\nthe field. This situation tempts the\nnewcomer to go after his share of ,the\ntrade by cutting prices. When one\nstation out of ten makes a cut in prices\nto attract attention to its arrival and\nget business, this always results in\nbringing down prices in the same de\ngree at the nine other stations.\nThat, in brief, is the marketing sit\nuation existing today over much of the\nUnited States. Such conditions could\nnot have been brought about but for\nthe pressure of excessive refinery out\nput seeking a market. To go back still\ni further, the refinery oversupply would\nnot be what it is today were it not for\ni the cumulative surplus of crude oil\npressing upon the manufacturer and\ninviting him to increase his plant runs.\nIt will be apparent from this that\nthe hope for relief lies almost entirely\nf with the producer of crude oil. If raw\nmaterial were brought to the surface on\na carefully planned schedule, laid out\ni to provide for all the requirements of\ns consumption, at the same time taking\naccount ol the necessity for a reason\nable draft on existing above\nFINANCIAL AND CLASSIFIED\ngfljc Sunday Star\nWASHINGTON, D. C., SUNDAY MORNING, SEPTEMBER 28, 1930.\nI ground, every department of the pe\ntroleum industry would come into\nalignment.\nReal Improvement.\nIt. is because some real improvement\nhas begun to show in the producing end\nof the business that I feel greatly en\ncouraged about the future. We have In\nthe United States approximately 37,-\n000,000 barrels of finished gasoline in\nstorage, enough by itself for a month's\nconsumption, without any current pro\nduction. This surplus or reserve of the\nfinished product is much too large in\nthe light of the increased flexibility of\nrefinery operations. It might be re\nduced materially at no inconvenience\nto the public and with a decided saving\nto the Industry.\nBack of this story of finished prod-\nucts is a much greater surplus or re\nserve of crude oil and partly finished\nstocks. No one is able to say Just how\nmuch these stocks should be to prove\nadequate. In an ideal situation they\nwould be large enough to cover working\nstocks and to fill in any deficiency in\nday-to-day production of crude un\ntil that is brought up to requirements.\nWhat we will all agree upon is that the\ntotal of 693,000.000 barrels is vastly\nabove the amount needed.\nThe combination of low prices for\ncrude production, voluntary and com\npulsory restrictions upon the principal\nfields and the growing understanding\namong producers of the economics of\ntheir situation has resuited in holding\ndown both drilling operations and flush\nproduction to a level which, if long\nenough maintained, should put the in\ndustry\u2019s house again in order.\nAt present we are drawing upon\ncrude in storage for about 50,000 bar\nrels a day. Gasoline stocks have been\nreduced during the peak of maximum\nconsumption, now coming to an end.\nThe statistical position will be im\nproved if during the coming Winter\nthere is no increase in gasoline stocks\nabove today\u2019s figures, which are more\nthan ample to meet all trade require\nments.\nPrecedent Cited.\nIn times past the industry has not\nbeen allowed to draw upon its reserve\nvery long before prices paid for crude\nwere advanced, and production thereby\nstimulated to make up the deficiency.\nWith the costly lessons from that ex\nperience in mind, it is to be expected\nthat the purchasing companies will be\nless likely to follow that policy in fu\nture.\nIf the same voluntary and compul\nsory measures of control are continued\nin force until a substantial reduction\nhas been made in the stocks pressing\nupon the Industry, there should be a\nmarked improvement in all depart\nments, beginning with the producer\nhimself and eventually extending to the\nsmallest retail outlet.\nThe change will not be abrupt, but\nit should make Itself felt very gradu\nually, and with its progress should\nceme a recovery in earnings on the\neleven billion dollars' capital engaged\nin the oil business in the United States\n(Copyright, IMO. by North American News\npaper Alliance.)\nPASSING OF TRADE\nSTORM IS PREDICTED\nFinancial Leaders in 56 Cities\nBelieve That Improvement\nIs Near.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star. i\nNEW YORK, September 27.\u2014Business\nand banking leaders in 58 cities of this 1\ncountry believe the worst of the trade 1\nstorm is over. They agree that in- 1\nventories are low, money and credit are 1\nabundant, savings deposits are lncreas- 1\nmg, sales of some lines are expanding\nand business recovery is getting in quite\ndefinitely, but that the rate of improve\nment wili be slow. i\nThis survey, which does not include\nNew York City, was made public today J\nby the New York Stock Exchange firm\nof Tobey Sc Kirk. 1\nFrom the headquarters of the first\nr *L^ e\u00df T ve dtetrt St, Boston, comes 1\nword that ahoe manufacturing, woolen\ngoods and retail trade have improved.\nSchenectady, N. Y\u201e in the second 1\nFederal Reserve district, reports part- 1\nmp J\u00b0r e ntl electrical manufac- j\nturing and tapering operations in\nlocomotive building, a scarcity of\nmortgage funds and stoppage of the 1\nwithdrawal of savings deposits. Troy 1\nreports pay rolls increasing as shirt 1\nmanufacturing expands.\nh e i? lrd Fed eral Reserve district,\nPhiladeiphia looks for good business In\nwool cotton yam, leather and cigars,\nbut the tobacco crop is very poor and\nhSr/Sff 10 b to\u00df\noptKffi taT.nss\" <lMrlCte\n(Copyright, 1930.)\nNEW SHORT RAIL LINK\nTO PACIFIC SOON OPEN\nSanta Fe to Tie Up With Orient\nLine of Mexico After\n30-Year Wait.\nBy the Associated Press.\nPRpiDIo, Tex., September 27.\nFulfillment after more than 30 years\nof an extravagant dream of a short\nroute to the Pacific and the Orient was\nIn the hands of a group of track work\ners today.\nA locomotive steamed into Presidio\nyesterday, ending the town\u2019s quarter-of\n-a-century wait for rail transportation\nand bringing material to complete to\nday the link between the Atchison, To\npeka St Santa Fe and the Orient Rail\nroad of Mexico.\nThus the route started many years\nago by the late Arthur Stilwell becomes\nthe newest rail link between the United\nStates and Mexico and fulfills his\ndream of a route to Topolabampo, on\nthe Gulf of Lower California.\nThe Mexican division of the Orient\nended at OJinaga. The American sec\ntion of the proposed Pacific route, be\ngun at Wichita, Kans., extended to\nAlpine. Tex. Later it became Involved\nin financial difflfcultlea. The Santa Fe\npurchased the Orient and completed\nthe link through Presidio to OJinaga.\nMany Mexican and Southwestern\nAmerican cities, Including Kansas'City,\nStilwell\u2019s former home, are planning\na celebration on November 1 of the\nline\u2019s completion.\nll\nWESTINGHOUSE ANNUITY.\nAbout 50,000 employes of the West\ninghouse Electric St Manufacturing 00.\nand its subsidiaries are eligible to bene\nfit wider an annuity plan arranged on\na trustee basis. The annuity unite are\nissued on the basis of length of service\nand yearly earnings with bonus addi\ntions.\nDECLINE IN STOCKS\nIS AGGRAVATED BY\nCOMMODIiIES DROP\nSpeculative Markets Slump\nin Week of Adverse Devel\nopments\u2014Bears Active.\nSYMPTOMS OF RECOVERY\nIN BUSINESS APPARENT\nRecent Heavy Selling Movement in\nSecurities May Bring Tem\nporary Rebound.\nBY GEORGE T. HUGHES.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, September 27.\u2014T0 pre\nserve a Judicial frame of mind, with\nspeculative markets presenting the pic\nture of hysteria they have this week,\nhas been a difficult matter. Certainly\nWall Street has found it so. Optimists\nare as scarce as the proverbial hens\u2019\nteeth and the pessimists have held the\ncenter of the stage.\nOn the face of things there has been\nlittle reason for cheer. In the first\nplace the commodity markets have con\ntinued their steady decline until wheat\nhas sold at the lowest since the depres\nsion year of 1907 and cotton at the\nlowest in 15 years. Sugar and silk have\nsold at new lows and about the only\nexception has been coffee, in which\nthere has been some recovery.\nUneasiness over the foreign situation\nis still in evidence, although the con\ncern is not as great as it was when\nthe results of the German elections\nwere first received. German dollar\nbonds dealt in on this side have had\nanother setback, although they have\nheld above the low point of the year.\nThe specter of a Russia overwhelming\nthe world not alone with grain, but\nwith goods at prices under the cost of\nproduction and at a level rendering\ncompetition impossible, has been an\nother strain on overwrought nerves.\nStocks Break August Lows.\nThen there has been a succession of\nomitted dividends and of poor earnings\nstatements, with predictions, more or\nless well Informed, of others yet to\ncome. It is no wonder that the stock\nmarket was unable to resist the on\nslaught of short selling and it is not\nsurprising that this short selling uncov\nered real liquidation, with the result\nthat the averages have broken through\ntheir August lows and are almost down\nto those of June.\nOs course there are some offsetting\nconsiderations. Money seeking employ\nment is in excessive supply, Judging not\nalone by the rates charged for day-to\nday loans, but for accommodation over\na longer term. Six-month collateral\nborrowings were made this week at\n2ft per cent, a rate unequaled since\nNovember, 19J5. Call loans on the ex\nchange have held officially at 2 per cent\nall week, but in the outside market\nthey have been made as low as 1 per\ncent.\nThis surplus of money has made\nitself felt in the bond market, where\nprices have gone to further new highs,\nbut so far only for obligations of the\nhighest grade. In the stock marxet\npreferred issues of unquestionable\nquality have followed the same course.\nIt is a curious commentary on the exist\ning condition that on one day this\nweek International Harvester common\nstock, representing one of the corpora\ntions doing business with the farmer\nand in great speculative disfavor on\nthat account, should sink to a new low\nprice for the year while the preferred\nstock of the same company went to a\nnew high.\nMoney Seeking Investment.\nCapital is timid, but it must find\nsomething to do and that something\ntakes the form of bidding competitively\nfor gilt-edge investment bonds and in\nvestment preferred stocks. If prece\ndent is any guide, this inquiry will\neventually spread to the best of com\nmon stocks.\nThe business news of the week, as\ndifferentiated from the market news,\nhas told of a moderate Improvement,\nseasonalperhaps, but welcome Just the\nsame. The most encouraging report\nhas come from the iron and steel trade,\nwhere the authorities have been tell\ning of operations at 61 per cent of ca\npacity against 58 per cent in the two\nprevious weeks. A growing interest in\nforward buying and a consequent stif\nfening in finished steel prices, with\nthe gain in bookings coming without\nthe aid of the two largest consumers,\nthe automobile Industry and the rail\nroads, but from miscellaneous sources.\nIn some cases, it is said that consumers'\nstocks have been so badly depleted that\nreplenishment is \u201cimperative.\u201d\nSentiment in business circles, again\nas contrasted with that in speculative\nquarters, is a little more cheerful. Thd\ntextile trade is a case in point, but as\na rule there is little tangible evidence\non which to base an opinion that the\nreal turn has come. Os one thing\nthere is no doubt. Weakness in stocks\nand falling prices for commodities react\nunfavorably on business and retard the\nimprovement which must eventually\ncome. It is all very well theoretically\nfor the banking Interests to stand aside\nand let the stock market take care of\nItself, completing its liquidation. That\nis the way to clear up a bad speculative\nsituation, but it does have the effect\nof leading the business man to believe\nthere is something overhanging both\nthe market and business, the nature of\nwhich has been kept a dark secret.\nUntil he is disabused of this idea, if\nwill be a dead weight on trade re\ncovery.\nTechnical Recovery Due.\nComing down to the Immediate situa\ntion: After the succession of days of\nviolent declines, the stock market is en\ntitled to some recovery on technical\ngrounds if for no other. No price move\nment ever shakes a straight line and the\ntrend downward this week has been so\ncontinuous that it is bound to turn,\ntemporarily at least. The best resist\nance has been shown by the Investment\nand semi-investment industrial and\nutility shares, just where it would be\nexpected to be shown if the market\nwere about to stage a comeback.\nFor the present, however, the oils, the\nmetal stocks and the motor shares have\nfew friends. Overproductio nos oil is\nstill an apparently insoluble problem.\nThe price of copper is down again and\nbelow the production cost of all except\nthe most efficient. Motor companies\nwill report third quarter earnings that\nare sure to make unpleasant reading for\nstockholders and meanwhile production\nis being held down to a minimum. New\nlows for the year or longer have been\nmade in many stocks in all three of\nthese groups.\nMuch the same situation exists in the\nrailroad list. The first 44 railroads to\nreport August earnings had a net\noperating Income 27.4 per cent lower\nthan in August. 1929, and 18.6 lower\nthan in August, 1928. ,Qp the other\n(Continued jp. Second Page.)\nI New President\n1\nI J\nT. M. KAUFMAN,\nWho was elected head of the American\nAssociation of Personal Finance Com\npanies at the conclusion of the annual\nconvention Just held in this city. He\nis from Indianapolis, Ind\u201e and is one\nof the youngest members of the organi\ncation. \u2014Underwood Photo.\ni\nBusiness News\n\nm\nRetrospect\nLatest Bank Merger Rumor\nin tke Local Financial\nl District Concerns Two\nInstitutions With a Com\nbined Capital of About\n$50,000,000.\nl\nBY I. A. FLEMING.\nMerger and consolidation are in the\nI air, and one need not be surprised at\nany rumor that may develop on the\nstreet, for there are banks and bank-\ners that a year ago\nwould have refused\neven to discuss\nsuch a thing as a\nmerger that are\ntoday looking for\na soft place to land\nand hoping for an\ninvitation to take\nthe plunge.\nNot that the\nyear, with all its\nchanges, has de\nveloped any weak-\nI nesses or troubles\nlin the banks, ex\ncept that it has be-\nIcome harder to\nI earn an honest\ndollar, more diffi\ncult to make the\nI. A. FLEMING.\ndividend requirements and, if one may\njudge from the signs of the times, the;\nturn for the better has not definitely\nset In.\nUnder these circumstances one lis\ntens with interest while a combination\nof a big trust company, heretofore un\nmentioned, and a national bank like\nwise unmentioned, are referred to as\nripe for the \u201cpersimmon\u201d pole.\nThere may be nothing more than ru\nmor in the report and yet one never\nknows what may happen in a prolonged\nsiege of dry weather. If the sugges\ntion should pass the rumor stage and\nbecome a fact the total resources of\nthe merged institution would not be\nfar from $50,000,000.\nThe Riggs National Bank, the out\nstanding financial institution in the\ncity, has total resources of $60,700,000.\nWashington Gas Awakening.\nAfter the quiet, peaceful career of the\nlocal gas company for so many years,\nprospering in a quiet way, accepting the\nwill of Congress in the matter of re\ntaining its capital stock at the amount\nnamed half a century ago, owning the\nentire stock of the Georgetown Gas Co.,\nand perhaps of the Rosslyn Co., but\nunable to operate as economically as\npossible, through refusal of Congress to\npermit the operation of all units as one\ncorporation, the company has now as\nsumed the aggressive, is forcing busi\nness, seeking benefits, natural gas, re\narranging schedules, etc., and promises\nto be an active entity in the future.\nGas bills are the smallest items in\nthe household economy of today. Other\nmeters may get on a rampage once in a\nwhile, but the gas registers are very\nsedate and rarely vary their speed.\nMergenthater\u2019s Earnings Fair.\nMergenthaler is one of the great in\ndustrial corporations that have not\nshut down their plants. The fiscal\nyear of the corporation is fast drawing\nto a close and the earnings for the\nperiod will show a very fair condition,\nwith business on the mend, and the\ndividend more than earned, and pay\nable for the current quarter with the\nadvent of October. Moreover the cor\nporation's position in cash and Gov\nernment bonds is very strong, while its\nbalance sheet is clear of obligations\u2014\nsomething not many industrial com\npanies can show at this time.\nPrices have been sagging on Mergy,\nbut that is just a sample of the pres\nent order of things, when the best is\nconsidered none too good. The news\npaper business is good and Mergy Is\ndistinctly a newspaper setter.\nA Clever Trick.\nBank bandits have to be rather smart\nthese days to make a decent haul and\nget away without Inciting the entire\ntown to, follow in a determined effort\nto even up an outrage.\nHere is the latest story from one of\nthe Southern States. A fine looking\nyoung man approached the paying tel\nler of a bank in one of the moderately\nlarge banks and said: \u201cWell, here I\nam. You see the gun. Over there on\nthat bench are eight men, all ready\nto shoot it out with you. I am also\nready and I have three men outside, so\nif you want to start something, just\nstart. But you would better take this\nflour sack and quietly put all the cur\nrency you have and any non-reglstered\nLiberties. These men (Indicating the\neight, men on the stool) will wait for\nsome time after I am gone to see that\nI get away and to quiet any disturb\nance. so don\u2019t start anything.\"\nAfter waiting for some time, the\ncashier called the police station and\nin a Jiffy had the eight men under ar\nrest. But there wasn't a gun on any\nof them and they were loud in protests\nthat they were not thieves, but honest\ni men out of work, who had been told to\nwait in the bank for the return of the\nbandit who was to furnish them work\na-plenty.\nGETS IRON CONTRACT.\nNEW YORK, September 27 (Special).\n\u2014General Bronse Corporation has been\n1 awarded the contract to furnish the\nSwedish wrought iron work for the new\n27-story Brooklyn Building of the New\nYork Telephone Co., one of the largest\ncontracts for this type of metal work\never placed in this country.\nFOREIGN BUSINESS\nOUTLOOK DECLARED\nSOMEWHAT BETTER\nUncertainty Ovef* German\nSituation and Weak Com\nmodity Prices Still Prevail.\nIMPROVED SENTIMENT\nIS NOTED AT MIDWEEK\nPrincipal Stock Markets Recover\ning and Exchange Rates\nAre Steadier.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, September 27.\u2014Cable\ndispatches to the Business Week give\nthe following survey of business abroad\nfor the week ending September 27:\nEurope\u2014Business is in a fitful state.\nThe uncertainty occasioned by the Ger\nman elections and the totally unexpect\ned renewal of softening commodity i\nprices\u2014particularly cotton, copper and\nwheat\u2014caused an appreciable check in\npreviously strengthening business con\nfidence and stock market buoyancy.\nLatest Indications are that sentiment\nis again improving. At midweek the\nprincipal stock markets were recover\ning and exchange oscillations were\nsteadying. Foreign credits in Germany\nwere reported little curtailed except for\nthe French, which have been heavily\nwithdrawn. Prompt Intervention by the\nReichsbank halted the incipient weak\nness of the Reichsmark, which is now\neasy. Both dollars and sterling gained\nagainst francs as the Reichsbank, in\nstead of further selling exchange, can\nnily exported gold to Paris in order\nto prevent frane appreciation on with\ndrawals of credits. The first shipment\nof $9,000,000 and the second of an\nIdentical amount is reported. Money\nis somewhat tighter in Berlin, but easier\nto the point of being plethoric in Paris\nand London.\nEncouraging Item*.\nTwo encouraging items of the week:\nMore liberal Far Eastern orders, espe\ncially for textiles; the Indian report\nthat, notwithstanding excessive world\nstocks of hessians, raw jute prices are\nfirming after a long decline. Due to the\nimportance of this fiber for packaging\nmaterials, it is considered a particularly\nsensitive trade barometer.\nThe focus of business as well as po\nlitical attention continues to pivot in\nGermany. Immediately at stake for the\nfuture administration is the continent\u2019s\nmost important economic unit. Elections\nmarked the first organized challenge of\nthe Versailles treaties and reparations,\nwhose revisicm even many neutrals feel\nis inevitable, and matters awaiting only\nan appropriate time and method. First\nfeaffs that a Nationalist victory would\nendanger the republican government\nand lead to policies jeopardizing Euro\npean stability have given place to the\nexpectation that the very degree of Na\ntionalist success will tend to unite the\nModerate Socialist and Bourgeois par\nties who still hold an actual majority\nbetween them. It is entirely probable\nthat the situation will turn, not upon\nelection Issues or foreign policies, but\nupon the already familiar domestic eco\nnomic problems, namely farm relief and\ntariff, unemployment subsidization, tax\nation and budget equilibrium.\nOpen grain markets are momentarily\nupset by Russian dumping, though opin\nion seems general that this condition\ncannot last lAig because of Russia's in\nability to maintain the present volume\nof exports.\nGreat Britain.\u2014Business is a bit\ndisgruntled over prolonged stagnation\nand the failure of the Initial seasonal\npick-up to develop more rapidly, but the\nnet position, viewed from London, is still\nme of relative improvement. Confidence\nrallied this week when unemployment,\nafter Increasing 79,137 last week,\ndropped 36,158.\nGeneral concern over the unemploy\nment situation, particularly since the\nunemployed number more than two\nmillions, and with the belief common\nthat increases cannot be stopped this\nWinter, has led to the formation of a\n\u201cnational council of Industry and com\nmerce,\" sponsored by Sir William Mor\nris, the motor manufacturer. This\ngroup will work for protected home\nmarkets and elimination of national\nwaste. Though considered \u2022by many\nonly a protectionist maneuver, the an\nnouncement of the council has had a\nmarked affect on popular feeling.\nFrance.\u2014Merchandising is reported\nseasonally more active, but new orders\nfor the basic industries\u2014notably coal,\niron, and steel\u2014are declining. The\nlocal cartel has reduced prices on steel\nproducts to meet the incipient inva\nsion of foreign competition following\nthe recent dissolution of international\nprice agreements. Money continues\nplethoric with a considerable withdraw\nal of credits from Germany. The ac\ncumulation of gold in Paris continues,\nbut is expected to cease during the com\ning month as tourist expenditures come\nto an end and seasonal raw material\npurchases begin. a\nThe latest crop estimate shows a\nfurther decline to 5,600,000 tons, com\npared with 9,500,000 a year ago. Im\nports this year are likely to exceed\n3,000,000 tons. One year ago the coun\ntry had an exportable surplus of 1,000,-\n000 tons. The stock market has stead\nied from the relapse occasioned by the\nGerman elections.\nPolitics Influence Business.\nGermany. Political factors have\nstrongly influenced the business out\nlook, particularly in the. unfavorable\nimpression created abroad as a result\nof election Issues. Further, there is ap\nprehension in business circles regarding\nthe attitude of the Bruenlng govern\nment to delay action until the reassem\nbly of the Reichstag. Leaders on the\nBerlin Stock Exchange urge the neces\nsity for Immediate formation of a new\nmajority in the government to remove\nthe present state of uncertainty which\nhas proved so detrimental to the stock\nmarket and to business generally.\nHowever gloomy the immediate out\nlook, recent sensational reports which\ncaused such heavy depreciation of Ger\nman securities on foreign stock ex\nchanges are considered grossly exag\ngerated by responsible business.\nYIELDS OF CANADIAN\nWHEAT ABOVE 1929\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nMONTREAL, September 27\u2014Wheat\nthreshing in the prairie provinces of\nCanada is 70 per cent completed, ac\ncording to the weekly crop report of the\nBank of Montreal. Yields are better\nthan those of last year, and up to the\npresent the grades are good; but fol\nlowing the recent wet spell some de\nterioration may result. In Quebec\nwet weather has delayed the comple\ntion of grain harvesting. Threshing\nshows a yield of good quality.\nClassified Ads\nPages 5 to 13\nConvention Leaders\nI\nv\nJm IL\n*\u00abM mrnmmmmmmm\n9ft 9\nb& jft\u00bb\nJohn G. Lonsdale (upper), president\nof the American Bankers' Association,\nwho will preside at the big fathering\nin Cleveland this week, and Rome C.\nStephenson, who will step into the\npresidency at the conclusion of the ses\nsions.\nInvestment Bond\nMarket Develops\nEasier Tendency\nHigh-Grade Issues Con\ntinue to Reach New\nPeaks, However.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, September 37.-\u2014Owing\nto poor earnings reportsT\u00dfP a number\nof American public utility and indus\ntrial corporations, there was a alight\ndrop in the general level of bonds dur\ning the past week. But this did not\nindicate the gerat strength of high\ngrade bonds, which continued to forge\nahead to new high levels.\nAt a time when the market had to\nabsorb a sizable amount of new offer\ning?, the volume of trading picked up to\na total of about $68,536,000 on the\nweek, compared With $49,694,000 last\nweek and $60,711,100 In the same week\nof 1929. This figure represents a dally\ntrading average of nearly $12,500,000\nfor the full five-hour session on the\nNew York Stock Exchange and is im\npressive not so much In Itself, but be\ncause It Is indicative of a much larger\ncounter trade besides the bonds sold on\nother exchanges.\nSelling in Foreign List.\nApart from the continued advance\nof seasoned favorites, the feature of the\ninvestment market was the heavy\nliquidation of German and other for\neign issues. Utterances of Adolf Hitler,\nthe German Fascist leader, at Leipzig\nthis week were so Inflammatory that\nnervous German investors flooded the\ncontinental markets with their own\ndollar and Internal obligations. The\nrecently Issued s>\u00a3s went to a 12-point\ndiscount in London and Amsterdam,\nthough the price kept 2 to 3 points\nabove those levels in New York, chiefly\nbecause there is no arbitrage trading\nin that particular security and Wall\nStreet\u2019s attitude is not so pessimistic as\nis that of those living nearer the scene\nof German political unrest. Austrian\nsecurities came under pressure on the\nreport of the resignation of the cabi\nnet of Chancellor Schober.\nToward the end of the week there\nwas a general recovery, and though\nthere was fresh selling in Europe on\nFriday, the price levels here were fairly\nwell maintained in most foreign dollar\ndescriptions*\nThe exceptions were the Issues of\nAustralia. London\u2019s persistent attitude\nof skepticism toward the Australian\ngovernment\u2019s good faith in Its proposed\neconomic reorganization drove those\nbonds down here.\nThere was a total of $125,381,807 in\nnew bonds offered here during the week,\nagainst $80,942,000 last week and $25,-\n373,000 In the same 1929 week. But\nthe movement of capital from Germany\nand Austria, and from England, too\nowing to the wave of pessimism that\nstruck that market during the week\u2014\nprovided funds to absorb the new offer\nings here and left a large surplus.\nStrength of Utilities.\nThe great strength of prime public\nutility bonds was a side feature, and\nthere was considerable switching from,\npublic utility common stocks to their\npreferred stocks or to their bonds. An\nanalysis of 95 such companies made by\nPnychon Sc Co. shows estimated gross\nearnings for the year at $1,370,300,000,\nagainst $1,333,000,000 last year and sl,-\n283,949,000 In 1928. However, the same\ncompanies reveal an increase in capital\ninvestment to $11,388,000,000, against\n$10,100,000,000 a year ago.\nRailroad bonds of the prime variety\nwere also harder. Standard Statistics\u2019\nindex of 10 of them standing at 109.8,\nagainst 109.4 a week ago.\n(Copyritht. 1930.)\nBANKER WANTslob\n30 YEARS; BUYS ONE\nWhen he was a boy, Weir Beall, now\nvice president of Harris, Forbes Sc Co.,\nNew York, wanted a zoo. Now, after\n30 years of collecting, handling and\ntraining wild, animals, Mr. Beiul has\nrealized his ambition. He has a zoo\nof his own.\nThree years ago Mr. Beall founded\nthe Long Island Zoological Park at\nOceanside, L. 1., and the park now\nhouses 107 wild animals, with ll train\ners and 1 Veterinarian to take care of 1\nthe beasts. The zoo contains elephant\nherds and performing lions which have\nappeared on vaudeville circuits, as well\nas one of the finest collections of mon\nkeys in the United States.\nCOMPETITION HELD\nOBSOLETE IN TRADE\nOF MODERN WORLD\nRudolph Spreckels Believes\nAnti-Trust Laws Are Detri\nment to Progress.\nGOVERNMENT CONTROL\nOF BUSINESS INVOLVED\nSngar Magnate's Statement\nRaise! Question of Curb on\nBig Monopolies.\nBY JOHN F. SINCLAIR.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nNEW YORK, September 27.\u2014Rudolph\nSpreckels, president of the Sugar Insti\ntute of America, has a national reputa\ntion for fearlessness. He had It when,\nalmost single-handed, he turned the\nbusiness grafters out of high places\nin San Francisco 15 years ago.\nIn Boston, recently, he threw another\nbombshell Into the business world by\nsaying \u201cthe old theory that competition\nIs the life of trade Is not applicable\nto present-day conditions.\u201d\nMr. Spreckels has always been con\nsidered a progressive. Many progres-\nslves still hold to the old theory of\ncompetition, and so believe in the rigid\nenforcement of the Sherman anti-trust\nlaws to maintain It.\nBut Rudolph Spreckels smiles. A busi\nness man and banker rcr many years,\nhe is convinced that the workings of\nthe anti-trust laws today hobble Ameri\ncan business.\nMr. Spreckels challenges the whole\nprinciple of competition in modern\nbusiness, says it is old fashioned and\nnot applicable to present-day conditions.\nHe wants It scrapped.\nUnrestrained monopoly is indefensible,\ntoo. Society can\u2019t yet delegate uncon\ntrolled monopoly to a few. Some form\nof government control is necessary. But\nthe larger question is this. Has the age\nof competition really passed?\nIn any event, the frank statement of\nRudolph Spreckels in Boston is a fresh\nand candid one, which will open up a\nsubject likely to be widely discussed for\nmany a day.\nFriday\u2019s Predictions.\nDr. David Friday) well known econ\nomist, formerly president of the Mich\nigan Agricultural College, has been look\ning into the business horoscope and has\nfound seven pertinent points upon\nwhich business recovery may be based.\nHe predicts that\u2014\n1. Wages will remain at their pres\nent level, with only a few slight down\nward readjustments.\n2. Prices for raw materials and farm\nproducts have probably reached their\nlow level and any changes will he up\nward.\n3. Prices for finished materials, ex\ncept in a few minor cases, are about\nstabilised.\n4. Dividends In 1931 will be less than\n10. per cent under the 1930 level and\nhigher than any other previous year.\n5. Interest rates will remain low un\ntil next Summer.\n6. Bond prices will continue up for\nthe next six months.\n7. Business, now showing a slightly\nupward trend, will accelerate this pickup\nlater this Fall, and show a modest im\nprovement right through 1931; while\n1932 \u201cwill probably be another record\nyear.\u201d\nPut this business prophecy in your\nscrap book and read It a year from now.\nFortune in Mice.\nThe channels of business often follow\nstrange and devious paths. Take David\nMayer, \u201cbreeder of white mice\"\u20143o\nyear* in the business. He has supplied\nmillions of white mice to laboratories,\nhealth stations and medical schools\nthroughout the world.\nMayer started his unusual business\nwith only 10 pairs of these rodents\u2014\nwhich seems like starting a business on\nthe proverbial shoe string. Today his\narm ships white mice to such distant\nIndia, China, Russia, and\nSouth America, and of course to all the\nexperiments! laboratories in Europe and\nMie United states. He has but two com\npetitors of any consequence in this coun\ntry-one in Philadelphia and the other\nin Kansas.\nsrgsL\nof 1 ex rim ented upon by\nstat Army doctors when\nthey were searching for a solution to\nthe yellow fever problems both in the\nPanama Canal Zone and the Philip\nNearly 4,000 of the white mice are\nshipped every week and the demand for\nProduct is constantly Increasing\nCol. Lindbergh carried two of Mr.\nMayer white mice, together with pneu-\nIn his flight to Quebec to\nsave the life of Floyd Bennett. These\n\u201cJ 1 1 18 were taken along In order\nthat the penumonia serum might be\ntried out if the physicians thought 1$\nnecessary.\nMayer headquarters in New\none learns that \u201cwhite mice breed\nfyrry three weeks, which is one of the\ncertain depend\nable reactions\u2014that makes them so in\nvaluable to science.\u2019*\nUse of By-products.\nPacking industry was one of the\ntifwm? ot scien-\nFff^\u201c en years ago it was said\nthat the packer in killing a hog used\neverything but the squeal d\ne\u201e\u00a3 th w businesses are now following\ninlSn*j\u00a3 nU i fft rl ?g planta study\ning in the latboratory Just how to use\ncommercially all the by-products\nTake the power which manufac\nplants use. In scores of plants\nit is developed from the steam used in\nsuch processes as heating, air condl-\nMonlng, dye vat work and bleaching.\nWhile power Is cheap a 1 back-power\nengine or turbine may be used P in\nsome Industries the cost of power and\nsteam Is 60 per cent of the total manu\nfacturing cost. So the two-fold use of\nshould cut this cost very ma-\nA recent example in this line is\nshoam by the Industrial Power Cor\nporation of Chicago, which has con\ntorted to supply electric power, gas\nand steam to the manufacturing and\n\u00aet\u00b0ck yards district. It cost $40,000,000\nto build the plant and is the first com\nprehensive combination of low tem\nperature distillation of coal with the\ngeneration of electric current, the pro\nduction of gas and the manufacture of\ndomestic fuel.\nPljnt the low temperature\ndistillation of coal will not only de\nvelop all the electrical power and steam\nnecessary, but there will be enough\nexcess gas to sell other Industries. In\naddition, other valuable by-products,\nsuch as tan, light oils and benzoll, will\nbe produced.\nThe Increasing use of by-product\npower should spell just one tUng\u2014\u00ab\nreduced cost of power to industry.","height":"25389","width":"19650"}}
